Do not truncate data that is required for workflow correctness. If checkpoint size must be capped, guard the write instead of mutating state. For example, serialize the payload first and skip the write (with a warning) when it exceeds a configured maximum:

```ts
const payloadText = JSON.stringify(payload, null, 2);
if (payloadText.length > CHECKPOINT_MAX_FILE_SIZE) {
  console.warn(
    chalk.yellow('Warning:'),
    `Checkpoint payload too large (${payloadText.length} bytes); skipping checkpoint write.`
  );
  return;
}
await writeFile(tempPath, `${payloadText}\n`, 'utf-8');
```

Alternatively, keep output and artifacts intact and truncate only human-readable fields such as node.response.

Capture the node id in the promise closure and propagate it with the rejection instead of relying on shared mutable state. For example, in the static wave executor:

```ts
const settled = await Promise.allSettled(
  wave.map(async (nodeId) => {
    ...
    try {
      const result = await runSingleWorkflowNode(...);
      return { nodeId, node, result };
    } catch (error) {
      const wrapped = error instanceof Error ? error : new Error(String(error));
      (wrapped as Error & { nodeId?: string }).nodeId = nodeId;
      throw wrapped;
    }
  })
);
```

Then use `firstRejection.reason.nodeId` when saving the failure checkpoint. Apply the same pattern to runWorkflowDagSegment so its own catch block records the correct nodeId without depending on the outer catch.
